nings":[{"name":"Cowley","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["English: habitational name from any of various places called Cowley. One in Gloucestershire is named with Old English <i>cū</i> ‘cow’ + <i>lēah</i> ‘woodland clearing’; two in Derbyshire have Old English <i>col</i> ‘(char)coal’ as the first element; and one near London is from Old English <i>cofa</i> ‘shelter, bay’ (see   Cove  ) or the personal name <i>Cofa</i>. The largest group, however, with examples in Buckinghamshire, Devon, Oxfordshire, and Staffordshire, were apparently named as ‘the wood or clearing of <i>Cufa</i>’; however, in view of the number of places called with this element, it is possible that it conceals a topographic term as well as a personal name.","Irish: shortened form of <b>Macaulay</b> (see   McCauley  ).","Manx: shortened form of Gaelic <i>Mac Amhlaoibh</i> ‘son of <i>Amhlaoibh</i>’ (a Gaelicized form of Old Norse <i>Óláfr</i>). For an alternative Manx form of the same patronymic see   Callow  ."],"variants":[{"name":"Coley","meanings":["English (Midlands): nickname for a swarthy person, from Middle English <i>coly</i> ‘coaly, coal-black’. The original short vowel is retained in the 16th century <i>colly</i> ‘dirtied with coal and soot’. Alternatively, a variant of   Cowley  .","Probably an Americanized form of Swiss German   Kohli   or   Kohler  ."]},{"name":"Cove","meanings":["English:","habitational name from a place called (the) Cove, examples of which are found in Hampshire, Wilts (a minor name in Leigh), Devon, and Suffolk, all from Old English <i>cofa</i>, which is recorded in literary sources with the sense ‘enclosed chamber’ but in placenames probably with extended senses such as ‘shelter, hut, building’, ‘hollow’ (in the case of the Devon name), and ‘creek, inlet’ (in the case of the Suffolk name).","nickname from Middle English <i>cof</i>, <i>cove</i> ‘eager, bold, courageous’ (Old English <i>cāf</i>)."]}]},{"name":"Eleanor","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["From an Old French respelling of the Old Provençal name <i>Alienor</i>. This has sometimes been taken as a derivative of   Helen  , but it is more probably of Germanic derivation (the first element being <i>ali</i> ‘other, foreign’ the second is obscure). The name was introduced to England by  Eleanor of Aquitaine  (  1122–1204 ), who came from Aquitaine in south-west France to be the wife of  King Henry II . It was also borne by Eleanor of Provence, the wife of  Henry III , and Eleanor of Castile, wife of  Edward I ."],"variants":[{"name":"Ellenor","meanings":["Variant spelling of   Eleanor  , the result of blending with   Ellen ."]},{"name":"Elenor","meanings":["From an Old French respelling of the Old Provençal name <i>Alienor</i>. This has sometimes been taken as a derivative of   Helen  , but it is more probably of Germanic derivation (the first element being <i>ali</i> ‘other, foreign’ the second is obscure). The name was introduced to England by  Eleanor of Aquitaine  (  1122–1204 ), who came from Aquitaine in south-west France to be the wife of  King Henry II . It was also borne by Eleanor of Provence, the wife of  Henry III , and Eleanor of Castile, wife of  Edward I ."]},{"name":"Elinor","meanings":["Variant spelling of   Eleanor ."]}]}],"historicEvents":[{"id":1705190,"age":12,"year":"1290","julianDay":2192224,"title":"Jews Expelled From England","description":"After years of anti-Semitic behavior, King Edward I expelled Jews from England in 1290.","jurisdictionLevel":1},{"id":1705191,"age":37,"year":"1315","toYear":"1317","julianDay":2201354,"title":"Famine Strikes Europe","description":"A famine caused by cold winters and wet summers across Europe caused millions to die due to starvation. Desperation from hunger caused high levels of crime, stampedes in bread lines in London, infanticide, and even cannibalism throughout Europe.","jurisdictionLevel":1},{"id":1705192,"age":50,"year":"1328","julianDay":2206102,"title":"First War of Scottish Independence","description":"The First War of Scottish Independence began after England invaded Scotland in 1296. The Treaty of Edinburgh was signed in 1328 which declared peace between the two kingdoms and brought the war to an end.","jurisdictionLevel":1}],"lifeSummary":"Eleanor Cowley was born about 1278, in Staffordshire, England. She married John Cowley about 1298, in Staffordshire, England. They were the parents of at least 1 daughter."},"et":{"abt  1278–Deceased":"umbes 1278–Surnud","1273–Male":"1273–Surnud","1298–1325":"1298–1325","1278–Female":"1278–Surnud","1315":"1315","1325":"1325","1278":"1278","1298":"1298","1273":"1273","abt  1278":"umbes 1278","1328":"1328","1317":"1317","1290":"1290","Staffordshire, England":"Staffordshire, England"},"fi":{"abt  1278–Deceased":"noin 1278–Kuollut","1273–Male":"1273–Kuollut","1298–1325":"1298–1325","1278–Female":"1278–Kuollut","1315":"1315","1325":"1325","1278":"1278","1298":"1298","1273":"1273","abt  1278":"noin 1278","1328":"1328","1317":"1317","1290":"1290","Staffordshire, England":"Staffordshire, England"},"fr":{"abt  1278–Deceased":"environ 1278–Décédée","1273–Male":"1273–Décédé","1298–1325":"1298–1325","1278–Female":"1278–Décédée","1315":"1315","1325":"1325","1278":"1278","1298":"1298","1273":"1273","abt  1278":"environ 1278","1328":"1328","1317":"1317","1290":"1290","Staffordshire, England":"Staffordshire, Angleterre","lifeSummary":"Eleanor Cowley est née environ 1278, à Staffordshire, Angleterre. Elle a épousé John Cowley environ 1298, à Staffordshire, Angleterre. Ils ont eu au moins 1 fille."},"de":{"abt  1278–Deceased":"um 1278–Verstorben","1273–Male":"1273–Verstorben","1298–1325":"1298–1325","1278–Female":"1278–Verstorben","1315":"1315","1325":"1325","1278":"1278","1298":"1298","1273":"1273","abt  1278":"um 1278","1328":"1328","1317":"1317","1290":"1290","Staffordshire, Englan